This paper deals with the computational complexity of equilibrium computation in discrete preference games, which is a topic in game theory (cs.GT). The paper also involves the study of social networks and metric spaces, which are topics in data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The use of algorithms to compute equilibria in these games falls under the category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The concept of balancing between intrinsic preferences and similarity to neighbors is related to social influence (cs.SI). Finally, the paper discusses the complexity of directed social networks, which is a topic in distributed computing and communication (cs.CC).
